zation or witness certification." "Identity verification or KYC for attestors." "Reputation scoring or trust ranking of attestors."], :stakeholder-question "How do I know that a claim was independently verified by enough\n  qualified attestors, that those attestations are still valid, and\n  that attestors face consequences for incorrect attestations?", :summary "Attestations are signed statements by independent attestors that bind a\n  claim outcome to a specific run and subject. The protocol manages\n  attestation lifecycle (active, superseded, revoked), verifies quorum\n  (k-of-n agreement), and holds attestors accountable through objective\n  slashable violation cases."} #:concept{:assumptions ["Evidence artifacts are produced deterministically from protocol state." "The registry hash includes each artifact's content hash in a canonical ordering." "The TSA is trusted and its root certificate is available for verification." "Concept labels do not change protocol validity."], :id :forensic/evidence-chain, :name "Forensic evidence chain", :out-of-scope ["Blockchain-level anchoring (L1 transaction inclusion)." "Merkle tree inclusion proofs or sparse Merkle trees." "IPFS/IPLD content-addressed publication." "Multi-party witness cosignature protocols."], :stakeholder-question "How do I know that the evidence from a protocol run is complete,\n  unmodified, cryptographically signed, timestamped, and consistent\n  from the first artifact to the final chain cursor?", :summary "The evidence chain binds each run's evidence records into a self-hashed,\n  self-verifiable artifact registry. A forensic-grade chain meets five\n  acceptance criteria: registry hash verifies against artifacts, hash is\n  signed by a known key, chain cursor verifies, RFC 3161 timestamp is\n  valid, and on-disk evidence is fully reconciled."} #:concept{:assumptions ["Confidence is distinct from pass/fail. A claim can pass with low confidence if coverage is thin. A claim can fail with high confidence 